d4d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/achieving-sustainable-development-goals-progress-establishing-integrated-national-financing-frameworks-asia-pacific-region", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "012cd241f441dc85481b98c9a84f25cfde98a2c9a4e945a7ac23a43bd2af249e"}}, "hash": "191f8864ffe6dde7880143e9e3b8f625bbee00c7e5e1a6b5d311c3ba94eaed16", "text": "the initiative is estimated at $90 billion. Some $40 billion of this has been pledged from the Government of China\u2019s Silk Road Fund, with the remainder expected to come from the AIIB, the BRICS New Development Bank, private equity and potentially the Asian Development Bank. The initiative focuses on shared economic growth and aims to yield substantial development dividends tied to market-based investments, thus potentially strengthening the quality of growth in the region and accelerating the achievement of the SDGs in the more than 70 countries through which the planned infrastructure will be passing.37 CHAPTER 1: REGIONAL CONTEXT 21 22 ACHIEVING THE SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT GOALS IN THE ERA OF THE ADDIS ABABA ACTION AGENDA 40. Impact investing is defined by the Global Impact Investing Network as investments made into companies, organizations, and funds with the intention to generate social and environmental impact alongside a financial return. Impact investing has four core characteristics: intentionality, investment with return expectations, a range of return expectations and asset classes, and impact measurability. https://thegiin.org/impact-investing/need-to-know/ 41. Note that these investments are not included in the figures because it is not possible to identify them within the data for the financing flows presented here. 42. These estimates are based on the 2016 Annual Impact Investor Survey by the Global Impact Investing Network. The data are based on a